      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property While Living Overseas
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Expat and non-resident owners regularly sell Queensland property without travelling back. Here is how the documents, tax, tenancy, and time zone logistics are actually handled.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a Brisbane property while living overseas is more common than most owners realise, and it is entirely manageable with the right team. The logistical pieces are real but solvable: documents can be signed remotely, an on-the-ground representative can handle coordination, and the legal and tax obligations are well understood by any Queensland solicitor experienced with non-resident sellers. The critical thing is to get the structure right at the start, because a surprise at the CGT stage or a missed signing deadline can be expensive to unwind.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the practical challenges, the three options for signing documents from overseas, the foreign resident CGT withholding regime, the main residence exemption position for expats, the tenanted property considerations, and the pre-settlement inspection logistics.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The typical scenario</h2>
      <p>An owner is living overseas for work, for lifestyle, or on a temporary posting. They bought the property before they left, or they are selling an investment they retained during the move. They want to sell without travelling back to Australia, either because the cost and leave time are prohibitive, or because their overseas role does not allow a trip on the timeline required. The property may be tenanted, owner-occupied by a family member, or vacant.</p>

      <p>The challenges fall into four groups: signing documents across time zones, coordinating the agent and solicitor on the seller's behalf, managing the pre-settlement inspection and handover, and navigating the tax implications of being a non-resident for Australian tax purposes. Each is addressable, but only if the structure is set up early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 1: sign via video with a Queensland solicitor</h2>
      <p>Most Queensland property documents can now be signed electronically. This includes the REIQ contract, the Form 6 agency authority that appoints the selling agent, conveyancing documents produced by the seller's solicitor, and trust account authorisations. The seller's Queensland solicitor verifies identity via video call (typically with passport on camera) and witnesses the electronic signing.</p>

      <p>For most expat sellers, this is the simplest option. It requires no advance preparation beyond appointing a solicitor who is comfortable with overseas video signings. Time zone coordination is the main constraint: signing calls need to be scheduled at a time that works for both the solicitor's Australian business hours and the seller's local time. For sellers in Europe or North America, this often means early-morning or late-evening calls.</p>

      <p>The electronic signing approach covers the contract of sale, the agency authority, and most standard conveyancing paperwork. It does not always cover every possible document in every transaction, so the solicitor should confirm at the outset that the full document set can be handled this way, and flag any that cannot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 2: appoint a power of attorney</h2>
      <p>A power of attorney allows a trusted family member, friend, or solicitor in Australia to sign documents on the owner's behalf. This is the traditional approach for long-distance transactions and remains useful for sellers who anticipate being unreachable during parts of the campaign or who prefer not to manage signing calls from overseas.</p>

      <p>A power of attorney can be prepared and executed before departure, which is the simplest arrangement if the seller knows they will be selling while overseas. It can also be executed overseas and registered in Queensland, though this requires the document to be signed in accordance with Queensland formalities, witnessed appropriately, and sometimes apostilled or notarised depending on the country of execution. A Queensland solicitor should draft or at least review the POA document before it is signed.</p>

      <p>The attorney appointed under the POA should be someone the seller trusts implicitly and who is practically available to attend solicitor offices, sign documents, and make time-sensitive decisions during the campaign. A professional attorney, such as the seller's solicitor, can also be appointed for a fee.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 3: use the solicitor as an attending representative</h2>
      <p>The seller's Queensland solicitor can act as a direct representative for specific purposes during the transaction. This includes attending settlement on the seller's behalf, coordinating with the buyer's solicitor, managing the trust account, and liaising with the agent for handover logistics. This is not the same as a POA: the solicitor is acting within their normal retainer scope, not holding a general authority to sign on the seller's behalf.</p>

      <p>In most expat sales, a combination approach works best: electronic signing for the documents that allow it, a targeted POA (to a family member or the solicitor) for any documents that do not, and the solicitor handling attendance at settlement as part of their usual conveyancing role. A good solicitor will propose this structure at the outset and cost it accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The foreign resident CGT withholding position</h2>
      <p>This is the area that most often produces unpleasant surprises. If the seller is a foreign resident for Australian tax purposes and the property sale price is above the foreign resident CGT withholding threshold (currently $750,000, with scheduled changes that remove the threshold entirely), the buyer is required by law to withhold a percentage of the sale price (currently 12.5%, with scheduled increases) and remit it directly to the Australian Taxation Office.</p>

      <p>The withheld amount is not lost, but it is held by the ATO until the seller lodges a tax return claiming it back. This can mean months between settlement and recovery, which affects the seller's ability to deploy the sale proceeds (for example, to buy another property or close out a loan).</p>

      <p>The key workaround is an ATO clearance certificate. If the seller is not a foreign resident for tax purposes, they can apply to the ATO for a clearance certificate before settlement. Providing the certificate to the buyer at settlement removes the withholding obligation entirely. The clearance certificate is free and can be applied for online, but processing time can vary, so it should be requested early in the campaign, not the week before settlement.</p>

      <p>Whether the seller is a foreign resident for tax purposes is a separate question from their citizenship or visa status. It is determined by tax residency tests, including how long they have been overseas, whether they have maintained an Australian permanent home, and other factors. A seller who is genuinely unsure should get a written tax position from their accountant before the campaign, so the CGT structure is clear before the contract is signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main residence exemption for expats</h2>
      <p>The CGT main residence exemption, which normally protects owner-occupiers from CGT on the sale of their home, is restricted or unavailable for foreign residents. Selling an Australian main residence while overseas as a non-resident can trigger CGT on the full gain, including the gain accrued while the property was a genuine main residence before the seller left Australia.</p>

      <p>There are limited life-event exceptions, such as terminal illness, death of a spouse or dependent, or divorce, but these are narrow and do not apply to most sellers. In general, a seller who has been overseas long enough to be a non-resident for tax purposes should assume that the main residence exemption is not available and factor full CGT into their net proceeds calculation.</p>

      <p>In some cases, selling before becoming a non-resident (before leaving Australia, or before the residency-change date in the relevant year) or selling after returning to Australia and becoming a resident again can preserve the exemption. This is a high-stakes timing decision with significant tax consequences, and it is exactly the decision that warrants specialist advice from an accountant or tax lawyer, not a general conveyancing solicitor, before listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenanted property: the notice period and lease considerations</h2>
      <p>If the property is tenanted, the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (QLD) governs what the seller can and cannot do. A tenant under a fixed-term lease has the right to see out the lease unless they agree otherwise, even if the property is sold (the buyer takes subject to the lease).</p>

      <p>A tenant under a periodic tenancy can be given a Notice to Leave for the property being sold with vacant possession, but the required notice period is set by legislation and must be followed precisely. Selling tenanted is also an option, and is often the most practical approach for overseas owners, because it avoids the risk and cost of a vacant property during the campaign.</p>

      <p>The property manager handling the rental should be looped in early. They will coordinate access for photography, inspections, and the pre-settlement inspection, and they are the practical interface with the tenant during the campaign. If the seller is planning to give notice and sell vacant, the notice needs to be timed against the campaign so that the property is vacant and presentable by the time the first open home runs, not still being emptied.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The pre-settlement inspection and handover</h2>
      <p>The buyer (or their representative) has the right to inspect the property in the days before settlement, typically 1 to 3 days prior, to confirm it is in the condition represented at exchange and that all agreed inclusions are present. For an overseas seller, this requires an on-the-ground contact to let the buyer in and to be available to address any issues that arise.</p>

      <p>In a tenanted sale, the property manager is the natural contact. In a vacant sale, a family member, friend, or the selling agent can handle access, though the agent's role formally ends at settlement rather than extending to post-inspection remediation, so the practical responsibility for fixing any issues still falls to the seller's team.</p>

      <p>Keys, remotes, access codes, and any other handover items need to be physically available at settlement. For overseas sellers, the most reliable approach is to deposit all items with the selling agent or the conveyancing solicitor during the campaign, with clear instructions on when they are to be released to the buyer. This avoids a last-minute courier from overseas on settlement day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The time zone factor</h2>
      <p>Time zone coordination is the single most consistent source of friction in overseas sales. Australian business hours overlap poorly with most of Europe and the Americas. Expect to take solicitor and agent calls outside your normal working day, often in the early morning or late evening local time.</p>

      <p>Email is the most practical coordination tool for day-to-day matters. Most campaign decisions, including strategy discussions, feedback from open homes, and offer considerations, can be handled by email with an agreed response window. Live calls should be reserved for document signing and for time-sensitive decisions such as offer negotiation.</p>

      <p>Build buffer days into every deadline. Document turnaround across time zones is slower than a purely local transaction, and settlements booked tightly against a time zone gap can fall over on a small delay. A solicitor who has done overseas transactions before will build this buffer into the contract dates as a matter of course.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Selling from overseas is entirely manageable with the right team. The components are: a Queensland solicitor experienced with non-resident sellers who is comfortable with video signings and CGT clearance certificates, a tax adviser who has given you a written residency position and explained your CGT exposure before you list, an agent who understands overseas vendor communication rhythms and is willing to work around time zones, a nominated on-the-ground contact (family member, property manager, or POA) for physical access and handover, and a clear signing and settlement structure agreed at the start so nothing is negotiated under pressure at the deadline.</p>

      <p>Get the tax advice first, before anything else. Get the signing structure second. Then list the property. In that order, an overseas sale is a well-managed transaction. In any other order, it risks becoming a series of avoidable problems.</p>

